{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_42","type":"agent_message","text":"{\"reviewer\":\"codex\",\"schemaVersion\":1,\"scores\":null,\"weightedTotal\":null,\"verdict\":\"WARNING\",\"issues\":[{\"severity\":\"P3\",\"location\":\"src/stores/space-store.ts:88\",\"description\":\"`loadMore` can still run while a full `fetchSpaces` reload is in flight because it does not guard on `isLoading`, and `fetchSpaces` leaves the old `hasMore`/`nextCursor` in state while the spinner is active. If a stale render or caller invokes `loadMore` during that window, it increments the shared `_reqId`, invalidates the full reload, may request the new filter with the old cursor, and can leave `isLoading` stuck because the stale `fetchSpaces` finally block skips clearing it. The r1 `isLoadingMore` stuck case is fixed, but the shared-token pattern still has this narrower inverse leak.\",\"recommendation\":\"Either prevent pagination during full reloads (`if (isLoading || !hasMore || !nextCursor || isLoadingMore) return`) and/or clear `hasMore`/`nextCursor` when starting `fetchSpaces`; a stronger version is separate request tokens for full reload and pagination. Add a regression test where `fetchSpaces` starts first and `loadMore` is invoked before it resolves, asserting `isLoading` is eventually false and stale cursor data is not appended.\",\"defer\":true,\"deferRationale\":\"P3 because the current UI normally hides the load-more button while `isLoading` is true, so this requires a stale render timing window or a non-UI caller. It is still a real store invariant gap and directly related to the shared `_reqId` race model.\",\"fixNow\":false},{\"severity\":\"P3\",\"location\":\"prisma/schema.prisma:153\",\"description\":\"The endpoint now returns only `limit + 1` rows, but the hot super-admin query is still `where status = ACTIVE` ordered by `updatedAt desc, id desc` without a matching composite index. With many ACTIVE spaces, the database can still scan/sort a large candidate set for each page, so WI-010 reduces response size but only partially addresses query-plan scale.\",\"recommendation\":\"Plan a migration for an index matching the global listing order/filter, for example status plus `updatedAt`/`id` ordering, and validate with the target database query plan. Consider owned/joined access patterns separately before adding broader indexes.\",\"defer\":true,\"deferRationale\":\"This is a database schema/performance follow-up requiring migration approval and production-like query-plan validation; cursor correctness and response-size compatibility are intact in this patch.\",\"fixNow\":false}]}"}}
